---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const buildDate = new Date().toISOString().slice(0, 10).replace(/-/g, '.');
---
<Layout
  title="About"
  description="α · intent vs alpha — the say-do gap of frontier AI labs. What this site believes, how it measures, what it isn't."
  spineGlyph="α"
  bgEquation="α : intent → alpha"
>
  <section class="hero" style="border-bottom: 0; padding-bottom: 1.5rem;">
    <span class="meta meta--accent">Colophon</span>
    <h1>What this is.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      Intent Alpha measures the gap between what frontier AI labs <em>say</em>
      in public and what they <em>actually staff for</em> in their open roles.
      That gap is the thesis; every dispatch is one measurement; the year-over-year
      record is the artifact.
    </p>
  </section>

  <article class="prose" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
    <h2>Thesis</h2>
    <p>
      A frontier AI lab is two voices at once. The first is the <em>public</em>
      voice — papers, blog posts, keynote talks, the framing on the
      homepage. The second is the <em>operational</em> voice — the open
      roles on the careers page, the departments where headcount actually
      grows, the verticals where the Account Executives are segmented.
      The two voices are rarely identical. The space between them is what
      this site calls the <em>intent–alpha gap</em>: the difference between
      stated direction and committed direction.
    </p>
    <p>
      The gap is the signal because hiring carries opportunity cost in a way
      that public messaging does not. A lab can say it cares about
      interpretability without staffing for it; it cannot staff for
      interpretability without ranking the work above some other use of the
      same hire. The gap is therefore the closest public proxy to revealed
      strategy that doesn't require insider information.
    </p>

    <h2>Vertical</h2>
    <p>
      <em>Frontier AI labs only.</em> Anthropic, OpenAI, xAI, Mistral, Cohere,
      Hugging Face, Scale AI, Stability AI, Perplexity, and the bot-protected
      tier (Google DeepMind, Meta-FAIR, Microsoft AI). Other companies — chip
      companies, hyperscalers, vertical SaaS — appear in the data layer as
      context, but the dispatches are about labs. This is a deliberate
      narrowing from the earlier 22-company panorama; the breadth was
      diluting the thesis.
    </p>

    <h2>Method</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>We pull job postings from public ATS endpoints — Greenhouse, Lever, Workday, Ashby, SmartRecruiters.</li>
      <li>We track changes over time — what roles appear, disappear, and cluster.</li>
      <li>For each frontier lab we compare the public messaging with the operational hiring shape.</li>
      <li>From that comparison, a single hypothesis is proposed per cycle.</li>
      <li>The hypothesis is then audited against pre-registered fail/pass criteria before publication.</li>
      <li>Each dispatch ships with an explicit confidence label, horizon, and structured falsification conditions.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Signature artifact</h2>
    <p>
      Year over year, the dispatches accumulate into the <em>Intent Alpha Index</em> — a
      flagship synthesis of the say-do gaps observed across frontier labs over
      the period. Year 1 is in preparation.
    </p>

    <h2>What this is not</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Not investment advice. Hiring data is a structural signal about what an organisation is building, not a signal about valuation.</li>
      <li>Not insider information — everything is sourced from public listings.</li>
      <li>Not a competitive ranking. Three-company references are ecosystem positions, not a leaderboard.</li>
      <li>Not a guarantee — hypotheses are falsifiable by design and tracked at <a href="/track-record/">/track-record/</a>.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Sources</h2>
    <p>
      Job postings are read from publicly accessible endpoints provided by the
      applicant tracking systems each company uses. We respect <code>robots.txt</code>
      and stated terms of service. Snapshots are version-controlled. The
      sampling map and all known coverage limitations are disclosed at
      <a href="/coverage/">/coverage/</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Cadence</h2>
    <p>
      This site is rebuilt and redeployed on every push to the source repository.
      Data analyses (cross-reference, vocab-shift, withdrawal-lifetime, diffusion-velocity)
      are recomputed against the latest snapshots and the outputs are committed back into
      the tree, so what you see and what the dispatches cite are the same files.
    </p>
    <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 1rem; text-transform: none; letter-spacing: 0;">
      Last build: <code>{buildDate}</code>
    </p>
  </article>
</Layout>
